Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.234 --> 00:00:06.200
Fitzpatrick: So this is our talk
about how to design--

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:08.601
Not so much how to design,
but how to think more in a--

00:00:08.601 --> 00:00:10.868
about users when you're
writing software.

00:00:10.868 --> 00:00:12.067
Collins-Sussman: Right.

00:00:12.067 --> 00:00:13.067
Well, actually,
let's introduce ourselves first.

00:00:13.067 --> 00:00:14.167
Fitzpatrick: Okay.

00:00:14.167 --> 00:00:15.334
Collins-Sussman:
What's your name?

00:00:15.334 --> 00:00:17.200
Fitzpatrick: My name
is Brian Fitzpatrick.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:18.434
Most people
call me Fitz.

00:00:18.434 --> 00:00:19.701
Collins-Sussman: My name
is Ben Collins-Sussman.

00:00:19.701 --> 00:00:21.567
I'm just Ben.

00:00:21.567 --> 00:00:24.501
And we are gonna
talk about--

00:00:24.501 --> 00:00:25.601
It's a very
subjective talk.

00:00:25.601 --> 00:00:26.667
It's based
on our experience.

00:00:26.667 --> 00:00:28.434
We come from
the open source world.

00:00:28.434 --> 00:00:30.634
We both worked on
subversion for many years,

00:00:30.634 --> 00:00:32.734
and now we're at Google,

00:00:32.734 --> 00:00:34.701
and we work on
an open source team,

00:00:34.701 --> 00:00:36.667
and we actually work on

00:00:36.667 --> 00:00:38.501
Google Code's project hosting
service.

00:00:38.501 --> 00:00:40.767
That's what I do. You do some
great management stuff.

00:00:40.767 --> 00:00:44.200
But what we do
essentially is--

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:46.167
everything we're talking about
is coming from our experience

00:00:46.167 --> 00:00:48.734
of working with
communities of users.

00:00:48.734 --> 00:00:50.567
Open source software,
closed source software,

00:00:50.567 --> 00:00:52.033
what is--
what kind of relationship

00:00:52.033 --> 00:00:54.133
do you have
with those users?

00:00:54.133 --> 00:00:56.167
Fitzpatrick:
And this is completely

00:00:56.167 --> 00:00:58.400
based on a series of anecdotes
that we're gonna tell

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:00.133
in addition to some
little bits of information,

00:01:00.133 --> 00:01:02.501
but most importantly,
this is a subjective talk.

00:01:02.501 --> 00:01:04.167
These are our opinions.

00:01:04.167 --> 00:01:06.033
If you disagree with them--
and that's fine--

00:01:06.033 --> 00:01:07.567
you can get your own talk,

00:01:07.567 --> 00:01:09.767
and have your own opinion
somewhere else.

00:01:09.767 --> 00:01:12.334
But seriously, we're--

00:01:12.334 --> 00:01:14.067
this is--we're sort of
gonna tell this

00:01:14.067 --> 00:01:15.400
through a series
of anecdotes

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:17.133
and things
that we've experienced.

00:01:17.133 --> 00:01:18.667
And that's it.

00:01:18.667 --> 00:01:19.834
Collins-Sussman:
Yeah, and there'll be

00:01:19.834 --> 00:01:22.234
time for Q and A
when we're done, so--

00:01:22.234 --> 00:01:23.634
First thing we want
to talk about

00:01:23.634 --> 00:01:25.601
is we're all
programmers here, right?

00:01:25.601 --> 00:01:27.767
Or most of us are,
so when you think about, well,

00:01:27.767 --> 00:01:29.601
what does it mean to have
successful software, right?

00:01:29.601 --> 00:01:31.133
There's a lot
of different metrics.

00:01:31.133 --> 00:01:35.100
You can say, well, it's really
fast, or it has a lot of users,

00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:36.334
makes a lot
of money, right?

00:01:36.334 --> 00:01:38.901
Or something,
or maybe it's really clever.

00:01:38.901 --> 00:01:40.100
But there are a lot
of things to think about

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:41.701
besides the technical side.

00:01:41.701 --> 00:01:44.167
It's not just about
how great your code is.

00:01:44.167 --> 00:01:46.434
It's actually
about...

00:01:46.434 --> 00:01:47.634
Well, there's a whole
social aspect to it

00:01:47.634 --> 00:01:48.968
that a lot
of programmers forget

00:01:48.968 --> 00:01:50.701
because we're so busy
writing code all the time.

00:01:50.701 --> 00:01:52.033
That's what we want
to talk about.

00:01:52.033 --> 00:01:54.033
Fitzpatrick: Right, when
you're thinking about software,

00:01:54.033 --> 00:01:56.267
engineers typically
think about the code,

00:01:56.267 --> 00:02:00.100
and some twist of algorithm,
or writing software,

00:02:00.100 --> 00:02:04.501
or a neat bit of Java
that they might write.

00:02:04.501 --> 00:02:05.501
Collins-Sussman:
That's the meat.

00:02:05.501 --> 00:02:06.968
Fitzpatrick:
Sort of the meat, right?

00:02:06.968 --> 00:02:08.133
So people tend
to think about

00:02:08.133 --> 00:02:11.267
the meat of
your application.

00:02:11.267 --> 00:02:13.601
However, what you
don't really think about

00:02:13.601 --> 00:02:16.400
is sort of, like, making
that look more presentable

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:18.901
and more appetizing
to our users, right?

00:02:18.901 --> 00:02:22.200
Typically, in the past,
engineers have seen

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:25.734
what happens when people put
sizzle onto a product, right?

00:02:25.734 --> 00:02:28.968
What you get is you get
a whole bunch of sizzle,

00:02:28.968 --> 00:02:30.834
and you get a whole
lot of no steak.

00:02:30.834 --> 00:02:33.667
Right? And so people
tend to be a little wary--

00:02:33.667 --> 00:02:35.634
Engineers tend to be
a little wary of doing that.

00:02:35.634 --> 00:02:37.133
Collins-Sussman:
Well, it's also usually--

00:02:37.133 --> 00:02:39.067
It's a relationship with
the marketing department, right?

00:02:39.067 --> 00:02:40.667
Ah, what are you doing
to our product?

00:02:40.667 --> 00:02:42.267
What are you
promising about it?

00:02:42.267 --> 00:02:43.834
What are you saying
about it, right?

00:02:43.834 --> 00:02:45.300
And I guess we're here
to talk about how

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:47.167
that is not necessarily
a bad thing.

00:02:47.167 --> 00:02:49.367
And trying to create
a better understanding

00:02:49.367 --> 00:02:51.434
of what does it mean to add
sizzle to your product--

00:02:51.434 --> 00:02:53.267
how do you make it
presentable to the public

00:02:53.267 --> 00:02:55.534
without feeling like
you're compromising your ideals,

00:02:55.534 --> 00:02:57.167
and, like, it's still
good software?

00:02:57.167 --> 00:02:58.934
Fitzpatrick:
Right. Exactly.

00:02:58.934 --> 00:03:01.734
So a lot of this stuff
is not gonna come

00:03:01.734 --> 00:03:03.033
as a complete
surprise to you.

00:03:03.033 --> 00:03:05.634
This is sort of an opportunity
to bring it together

00:03:05.634 --> 00:03:07.434
as well as to remind you
of some of these things

00:03:07.434 --> 00:03:08.934
that you might not
think of day to day

00:03:08.934 --> 00:03:10.868
when you're sort of
down in the trenches

00:03:10.868 --> 00:03:12.167
writing up an application.

00:03:12.167 --> 00:03:13.267
Collins-Sussman: Pull it
from their subconscious.

00:03:13.267 --> 00:03:14.434
Fitzpatrick:
Exactly.

00:03:14.434 --> 00:03:15.567
So we're gonna focus

00:03:15.567 --> 00:03:19.434
on three particular areas
in this talk.

00:03:19.434 --> 00:03:20.501
Collins-Sussman:
Yeah, so the first part,

00:03:20.501 --> 00:03:21.501
we're gonna talk
about marketing.

00:03:21.501 --> 00:03:22.601
What does it mean?

00:03:22.601 --> 00:03:24.767
How does it relate
to you as a programmer?

00:03:24.767 --> 00:03:26.701
And when you think
about marketing, right--

00:03:26.701 --> 00:03:28.067
Just say the word,
"marketing."

00:03:28.067 --> 00:03:30.100
What is the first thought
that comes to your head, right?

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.400
You probably think
about this guy, right?

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:34.934
Ah, run away.

00:03:34.934 --> 00:03:36.868
Want nothing to do
with him, right?

00:03:36.868 --> 00:03:39.100
Fitzpatrick: This guy
is all sizzle and no steak.

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:40.300
Right?

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:42.534
This is what you tend
to think about, okay?

00:03:42.534 --> 00:03:44.634
The real thing is
is that people are used to--

00:03:44.634 --> 00:03:46.267
when they think
about marketing or stuff,

00:03:46.267 --> 00:03:47.934
engineers are used to
being lied to.

00:03:47.934 --> 00:03:49.133
Okay?

00:03:49.133 --> 00:03:52.267
Engineers don't like
being lied to, okay?

00:03:52.267 --> 00:03:55.801
Anybody know when
 &lt;i&gt;Duke Nukem 3-D&lt;/i&gt; was announced?

00:03:55.801 --> 00:03:56.801
audience member:
[indistinct]

00:03:56.801 --> 00:03:58.801
Fitzpatrick:
1997. Okay?

00:03:58.801 --> 00:04:00.067
That was 11 years ago,

00:04:00.067 --> 00:04:02.234
and it took 'em 11 years
to go out of business.

00:04:02.234 --> 00:04:03.300
Collins-Sussman: 12.
Fitzpatrick: 12?

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:04.300
12 years.
Collins-Sussman: [laughs]

00:04:04.300 --> 00:04:05.434
Fitzpatrick:
12 years ago,

00:04:05.434 --> 00:04:07.033
but they never released
a piece of software.

00:04:07.033 --> 00:04:11.567
And that's the type of distrust
that I think we as engineers

00:04:11.567 --> 00:04:13.767
tend to harbor when we hear
about this type of stuff.

00:04:13.767 --> 00:04:15.501
Collins-Sussman: I think we're
just inoculated as a culture

00:04:15.501 --> 00:04:18.334
to any kind of advertising
or marketing, right?

00:04:18.334 --> 00:04:19.968
We're skeptical
about everything we hear,

00:04:19.968 --> 00:04:22.734
'cause we just believe that
marketing and advertising people

00:04:22.734 --> 00:04:24.400
are always lying
all the time, right?

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:26.267
Programmers really don't
want anything to do with it.

00:04:26.267 --> 00:04:28.000
Programmers are
very logical people,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.234
they're obsessed
with finding the truth,

00:04:30.234 --> 00:04:31.567
finding the true thing,

00:04:31.567 --> 00:04:34.167
and only talking about,
you know, logical, true stuff.

00:04:34.167 --> 00:04:36.968
I mean, we live
with compilers.

00:04:36.968 --> 00:04:40.634
Those are the tools
we use every single day, right?

00:04:40.634 --> 00:04:41.734
We like order,
we like predictability,

00:04:41.734 --> 00:04:43.067
we like control.

00:04:43.067 --> 00:04:45.934
We don't like listening
to people try to spin things

00:04:45.934 --> 00:04:47.534
and then we're sort of
left to guessing

00:04:47.534 --> 00:04:49.501
as to what's real
and what's not.

00:04:49.501 --> 00:04:51.567
Fitzpatrick: Five years ago
I was the vice president

00:04:51.567 --> 00:04:54.534
of public relations for
the Apache Software Foundation,

00:04:54.534 --> 00:04:57.133
which is an organization
made up almost exclusively

00:04:57.133 --> 00:04:58.868
of engineers.

00:04:58.868 --> 00:05:00.267
And, you know,
most people thought,

00:05:00.267 --> 00:05:01.701
oh, we shouldn't
have to do PR.

00:05:01.701 --> 00:05:02.868
If we write
the best software,

00:05:02.868 --> 00:05:04.501
people are just
gonna come use it.

00:05:04.501 --> 00:05:07.801
And meanwhile,
other web servers

00:05:07.801 --> 00:05:10.133
and other pieces of software
that competed with Apache

00:05:10.133 --> 00:05:13.567
were eating their lunch
because when an analyst

00:05:13.567 --> 00:05:14.968
would come up to a commercial
company and say--

00:05:14.968 --> 00:05:16.167
Collins-Sussman:
"Where's your white paper?"

00:05:16.167 --> 00:05:17.334
Fitzpatrick:
"Where's your white paper?"

00:05:17.334 --> 00:05:18.367
and "We want you
to answer this, this, this,

00:05:18.367 --> 00:05:19.834
this, and this
about your software,"

00:05:19.834 --> 00:05:22.501
and the company would, you know,
have four or five PR flacks

00:05:22.501 --> 00:05:24.000
get down on their knees
and then worship the analyst

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:25.400
and tell them
how wonderful they are,

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:27.400
and they do all their work
for them and hand it to them.

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:28.968
And an analyst
shows up at Apache

00:05:28.968 --> 00:05:30.501
for one project
in particular,

00:05:30.501 --> 00:05:31.767
which will remain nameless,

00:05:31.767 --> 00:05:34.067
and says, "Hey, we want
to know this, this, and this

00:05:34.067 --> 00:05:35.767
"about your projects,
and blah, blah, blah,

00:05:35.767 --> 00:05:37.033
"we're gonna write
a paper, et cetera,

00:05:37.033 --> 00:05:38.334
and go do all this work,"

00:05:38.334 --> 00:05:41.100
and their basic response was,
"Go screw yourself.

00:05:41.100 --> 00:05:43.400
Join the mailing list
and find it yourself."

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:44.868
Collins-Sussman: "Go read,
you know. Go read our docs."

00:05:44.868 --> 00:05:45.868
Fitzpatrick: Right.

00:05:45.868 --> 00:05:47.033
Collins-Sussman:
"Not our problem."

00:05:47.033 --> 00:05:48.901
Fitzpatrick: So the best
approach probably lies

00:05:48.901 --> 00:05:51.400
somewhere in between
those two approaches.

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:53.567
The sort of sycophantic
begging, and then

00:05:53.567 --> 00:05:55.901
the, like, "Go read
the mailing list."

00:05:55.901 --> 00:05:57.167
Collins-Sussman:
Absolutely.

00:05:57.167 --> 00:06:00.334
I mean, the other thing
that programmers like to do

00:06:00.334 --> 00:06:02.534
is especially when
it comes to legal things,

00:06:02.534 --> 00:06:04.934
they start trying
to interpret the law, right?

00:06:04.934 --> 00:06:06.667
I mean, there's a lot
of issues that have to do

00:06:06.667 --> 00:06:08.968
with marketing and PR,
and they always get entangled

00:06:08.968 --> 00:06:11.701
with legal discussions, right,
licensing,

00:06:11.701 --> 00:06:13.868
and what are we allowed
to say and or not say,

00:06:13.868 --> 00:06:17.167
and programmers love to look
at laws and licenses

00:06:17.167 --> 00:06:19.634
and try to process
them like code,

00:06:19.634 --> 00:06:22.000
when in fact, if you are
a lawyer, or you know lawyers,

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:23.868
they will laugh at you if you
talk about that idea, right?

00:06:23.868 --> 00:06:26.300
'Cause the legal system
is not perfectly rational.

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:27.467
It's not logical.
Fitzpatrick: What?

00:06:27.467 --> 00:06:29.133
Collins-Sussman:
I know, it's crazy.

00:06:29.133 --> 00:06:30.968
Fitzpatrick: Yeah, if you're
ever talking about something

00:06:30.968 --> 00:06:33.834
legal with a license, you say,
"well, it should do something,"

00:06:33.834 --> 00:06:35.167
stop yourself right there

00:06:35.167 --> 00:06:36.601
because you're clearly
going down the wrong path.

00:06:36.601 --> 00:06:38.000
Collins-Sussman:
Absolutely.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.601
Fitzpatrick: But beyond this
sort of obsession with truth

00:06:39.601 --> 00:06:44.467
is that we expect some sort
of a meritocracy, I guess.

00:06:44.467 --> 00:06:48.300
That people put the most
effort into something

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:51.067
or the best
technical thing would win.

00:06:51.067 --> 00:06:52.434
Collins-Sussman:
Right, but if that were true,

00:06:52.434 --> 00:06:54.234
we'd all be using Betamax--

00:06:54.234 --> 00:06:56.300
well, nobody uses
VHS either anymore--

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:57.567
but the classic
story, right?

00:06:57.567 --> 00:06:58.934
Fitzpatrick:
But it had a good run.

00:06:58.934 --> 00:07:01.367
Collins-Sussman: Betamax
was technically superior to VHS,

00:07:01.367 --> 00:07:02.701
and yet VHS won, right?

00:07:02.701 --> 00:07:04.968
So not everything--
the technically superior product

00:07:04.968 --> 00:07:06.400
does not always
win, right?

00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:08.968
That is not the only metric
you need to think about

00:07:08.968 --> 00:07:10.267
when you're saying,

00:07:10.267 --> 00:07:11.834
"well, how is my product
gonna be successful?"

00:07:11.834 --> 00:07:13.434
You need some sizzle.
Fitzpatrick: Right.

00:07:13.434 --> 00:07:14.501
Collins-Sussman:
To some degree you need it.

00:07:14.501 --> 00:07:15.834
Whether you like it or not.

00:07:15.834 --> 00:07:16.834
Fitzpatrick: So the point
that I try to make is that

00:07:16.834 --> 00:07:18.501
truth is actually fungible.

00:07:18.501 --> 00:07:20.634
Okay, there are
different shades of truth,

00:07:20.634 --> 00:07:22.334
and this is a mean that
I've been trying to propagate

00:07:22.334 --> 00:07:25.067
for years, which is that
perception--not procession--

00:07:25.067 --> 00:07:27.534
but perception
is 9/10 of the law.

00:07:27.534 --> 00:07:28.767
What it comes
down to is that--

00:07:28.767 --> 00:07:29.934
Collins-Sussman:
First perception.

00:07:29.934 --> 00:07:32.100
Fitzpatrick:
Exactly.

00:07:32.100 --> 00:07:35.100
What people see is the reality,
whether or not it's true.

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:36.434
What people will believe.

00:07:36.434 --> 00:07:38.267
And marketers have used that
to their advantage

00:07:38.267 --> 00:07:39.567
for years and years
and years.

00:07:39.567 --> 00:07:41.167
There's no reason
that we as engineers

00:07:41.167 --> 00:07:42.501
shouldn't do that as well.

00:07:42.501 --> 00:07:44.467
Collins-Sussman: Typically
in the first 2, 5 minutes

00:07:44.467 --> 00:07:46.133
of using a piece of software,

00:07:46.133 --> 00:07:47.767
you formed an opinion about it,
right?

00:07:47.767 --> 00:07:49.634
It doesn't matter whether
you've--you know,

00:07:49.634 --> 00:07:51.033
whether you read the docs

00:07:51.033 --> 00:07:53.033
or you should have read
the docs, right,

00:07:53.033 --> 00:07:55.434
or you get an opinion
about it very quickly.

00:07:55.434 --> 00:07:58.367
There's either a good
or a bad barrier to entry,

00:07:58.367 --> 00:07:59.901
and then you've
made up your--

00:07:59.901 --> 00:08:01.601
and that's the truth
you now live with.

00:08:01.601 --> 00:08:03.434
You have a certain feeling
about this software,

00:08:03.434 --> 00:08:05.868
whether you were fair
in judging it or not.

00:08:05.868 --> 00:08:06.968
Fitzpatrick:
Well, with Subversion

00:08:06.968 --> 00:08:08.100
we were particularly
conservative

00:08:08.100 --> 00:08:09.901
in calling Subversion 1.0

00:08:09.901 --> 00:08:12.200
because when it comes
to a version control system,

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:13.601
if it loses your data,

00:08:13.601 --> 00:08:15.133
you're probably
never gonna come back.

00:08:15.133 --> 00:08:18.434
Okay, data--that's sort of
an important thing.

00:08:18.434 --> 00:08:20.067
It's not really the best,

00:08:20.067 --> 00:08:22.767
technically the best version
control system out there,

00:08:22.767 --> 00:08:24.501
but it was generally
perceived

00:08:24.501 --> 00:08:28.133
by people as being
a good thing.

00:08:28.133 --> 00:08:29.901
Moving along,

00:08:29.901 --> 00:08:31.801
one other thing
that you can sort of have

00:08:31.801 --> 00:08:32.968
the sizzle in the steak

00:08:32.968 --> 00:08:34.734
is that under-promise
and over-deliver.

00:08:34.734 --> 00:08:37.033
You still have great things
to give to people,

00:08:37.033 --> 00:08:38.968
you still have a great
piece of software,

00:08:38.968 --> 00:08:40.534
but you don't have
to tell them everything

00:08:40.534 --> 00:08:41.634
that you want
to give, maybe,

00:08:41.634 --> 00:08:43.267
so you tell 'em
the first few things.

00:08:43.267 --> 00:08:44.834
I come from New Orleans,

00:08:44.834 --> 00:08:46.868
and in New Orleans
we talk about lagniappe,

00:08:46.868 --> 00:08:48.501
okay, a little bit
of something extra.

00:08:48.501 --> 00:08:50.300
Like you buy
a dozen doughnuts,

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:51.734
you get an extra doughnut
free.

00:08:51.734 --> 00:08:54.000
You buy five pounds of meat and
you get a pound of liver free.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:55.801
I don't know why that was
ever a good thing,

00:08:55.801 --> 00:08:57.267
but apparently that's the way
it worked back in the day.

00:08:57.267 --> 00:08:58.434
Collins-Sussman:
But you certainly

00:08:58.434 --> 00:08:59.667
don't market that, right?

00:08:59.667 --> 00:09:02.501
You don't write that
in the coupons, right?

00:09:02.501 --> 00:09:05.133
It's just one
of those things you do.

00:09:05.133 --> 00:09:06.367
In the same way
we're talking

00:09:06.367 --> 00:09:07.734
about under-promise
and over-delivering,

00:09:07.734 --> 00:09:09.868
Google, as a policy,
doesn't pre-announce products.

00:09:09.868 --> 00:09:12.767
We don't send out endless
press releases saying,

00:09:12.767 --> 00:09:13.934
"We're working
on this cool thing.

00:09:13.934 --> 00:09:16.834
It'll be done
this quarter."

00:09:16.834 --> 00:09:19.834
'Cause then essentially
we set ourselves up for failure.

00:09:19.834 --> 00:09:23.133
It's a matter of, you know,
surprising people,

00:09:23.133 --> 00:09:24.501
and saying,
"Isn't that wonderful?"

00:09:24.501 --> 00:09:26.033
Fitzpatrick: You set your
expectations really high,

00:09:26.033 --> 00:09:27.234
and then you wind up
with something

00:09:27.234 --> 00:09:28.868
people aren't
looking forward to.

00:09:28.868 --> 00:09:31.501
So that's sort of
the marketing angle,

00:09:31.501 --> 00:09:33.901
and we want to talk a little bit
about customer service.

00:09:33.901 --> 00:09:35.567
Now, sort of close your eyes
for a second and think--

00:09:35.567 --> 00:09:37.934
what do you think about when
you hear "customer service"?

00:09:37.934 --> 00:09:38.934
Collins-Sussman: Mmm...

00:09:38.934 --> 00:09:39.934
Fitzpatrick:
In this day and age,

00:09:39.934 --> 00:09:41.367
especially
in the United States,

00:09:41.367 --> 00:09:42.667
people think
of customer service,

00:09:42.667 --> 00:09:46.467
they think of a service-oriented
industry where someone

00:09:46.467 --> 00:09:48.934
is doing something
for someone else,

00:09:48.934 --> 00:09:50.267
and sort of a one-on-one
kind of thing.

00:09:50.267 --> 00:09:51.467
Collins-Sussman: But it's
also sort of considered

00:09:51.467 --> 00:09:52.634
the bottom
of the ladder, right?

00:09:52.634 --> 00:09:54.200
Like, working the help desk
in a company.

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:56.834
Oh, my, no.
Customer service tech support.

00:09:56.834 --> 00:10:00.000
Got to get out of there.
What a waste of time, right?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:01.501
Fitzpatrick: So we have
a graph here

00:10:01.501 --> 00:10:04.534
that we spent
minutes researching.

00:10:04.534 --> 00:10:07.334
It's basically--
you start off, and you--

00:10:07.334 --> 00:10:09.167
if you have
a successful piece of software,

00:10:09.167 --> 00:10:10.667
you're going to get
more users over time.

00:10:10.667 --> 00:10:12.200
That's what
everybody wants, I think.

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:13.701
I don't think there's
anyone in this room

00:10:13.701 --> 00:10:16.334
who writes software that doesn't
want more people to use it.

00:10:16.334 --> 00:10:18.434
The problem is is that
as you add users,

00:10:18.434 --> 00:10:20.033
you don't stop
writing code.

00:10:20.033 --> 00:10:22.501
You continue
adding to your--

00:10:22.501 --> 00:10:24.300
the complexity
of your application.

00:10:24.300 --> 00:10:25.901
Collins-Sussman:
More and more features,

00:10:25.901 --> 00:10:28.501
more and more
feature creep, at least.

00:10:28.501 --> 00:10:29.834
Maybe the users
are asking--

00:10:29.834 --> 00:10:31.968
Maybe the power users
are asking for more features

00:10:31.968 --> 00:10:34.200
so you're like, "Great, more
code, throw it in, throw it in.

00:10:34.200 --> 00:10:35.467
Look how great this is."

00:10:35.467 --> 00:10:37.334
Fitzpatrick: The problem
is is that as time goes on,

00:10:37.334 --> 00:10:38.834
and your user base widens,

00:10:38.834 --> 00:10:40.667
you attract less tech-savvy
users.

00:10:40.667 --> 00:10:42.000
Okay?

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.601
And the combination of these
three different factors

00:10:44.601 --> 00:10:46.734
results in an exponential
increase in despair.

00:10:46.734 --> 00:10:47.901
Collins-Sussman:
Very carefully measured.

00:10:47.901 --> 00:10:49.133
Fitzpatrick:
Very carefully measured.

00:10:49.133 --> 00:10:50.300
Exactly.

00:10:50.300 --> 00:10:52.501
But the point is is that
this is something

00:10:52.501 --> 00:10:53.767
that's really
important to realize,

00:10:53.767 --> 00:10:55.467
is that this complexity
is very difficult

00:10:55.467 --> 00:10:58.534
for users to sort of
grok and understand,

00:10:58.534 --> 00:11:00.567
but you have to listen
to them.

00:11:00.567 --> 00:11:02.167
This is part
of customer service.

00:11:02.167 --> 00:11:04.334
You shouldn't just
assume that they're dumb.

00:11:04.334 --> 00:11:05.968
We had a talk
yesterday at the ignite

00:11:05.968 --> 00:11:07.968
that was just fantastic
where they were talking

00:11:07.968 --> 00:11:11.567
about, you know,
give your users the real thing.

00:11:11.567 --> 00:11:12.901
Don't give them
some dumbed-down,

00:11:12.901 --> 00:11:14.133
toy version of that thing.

00:11:14.133 --> 00:11:15.167
I think that's a great point.

00:11:15.167 --> 00:11:16.467
Collins-Sussman:
Right.

00:11:16.467 --> 00:11:18.167
I mean, they're not
dumb people necessarily--

00:11:18.167 --> 00:11:19.701
Sure, a few of them
out there are dumb,

00:11:19.701 --> 00:11:22.501
but there's not a safe
assumption to assume

00:11:22.501 --> 00:11:25.868
that just because somebody's
asking a question or needs help

00:11:25.868 --> 00:11:27.400
or doesn't understand something
about your software

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:30.834
that they're inherently
dumb in general,

00:11:30.834 --> 00:11:32.300
or they're just not
techie people, right?

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:33.734
I mean,
if something is wrong

00:11:33.734 --> 00:11:35.367
you actually need
to hear what's going on,

00:11:35.367 --> 00:11:38.400
and the first step
is not be condescending.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:40.934
It's to respect
and listen carefully

00:11:40.934 --> 00:11:42.367
and really try to get
some empathy going

00:11:42.367 --> 00:11:43.901
with what
they're experiencing.

00:11:43.901 --> 00:11:47.100
I mean, we're so used to being
holed up with our compilers

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:50.200
and our code that we sort of
lose all perspective

00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:52.734
of what the rest
of the world sees.

00:11:52.734 --> 00:11:54.400
Fitzpatrick: Right, and people
just want to be heard.

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:57.734
So give them
an opportunity to be heard.

00:11:57.734 --> 00:12:00.434
Even if they're not
writing code for you,

00:12:00.434 --> 00:12:01.934
they can give you
valuable feedback.

00:12:01.934 --> 00:12:02.934
Collins-Sussman:
You can let them

00:12:02.934 --> 00:12:04.767
file bugs
in your issue tracker

00:12:04.767 --> 00:12:06.534
and respond with them,

00:12:06.534 --> 00:12:07.834
so then they
at least feel like

00:12:07.834 --> 00:12:10.467
you are listening
to them in some degree.

00:12:10.467 --> 00:12:13.400
Fitzpatrick: An example of this
is Google Moderator.

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:14.834
We've--you know, I mean...
Collins-Sussman: Oh, yeah.

00:12:14.834 --> 00:12:16.367
Fitzpatrick: The White House
recently used that

00:12:16.367 --> 00:12:18.200
to sort of get
questions from people.

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:20.501
And setting up a moderator
instance for, you know--

00:12:20.501 --> 00:12:21.501
What do you guys want?

00:12:21.501 --> 00:12:22.667
Let's get some feedback,

00:12:22.667 --> 00:12:24.367
and let's get some people
to vote it off.

00:12:24.367 --> 00:12:26.801
In the issue tracker,
users can star things,

00:12:26.801 --> 00:12:28.234
and you can sort of
see themes.

00:12:28.234 --> 00:12:31.434
And we notice this very clearly
in Google Code itself.

00:12:31.434 --> 00:12:33.934
We have an issue tracker
for the product.

00:12:33.934 --> 00:12:35.734
and we heard very clearly
different pain points

00:12:35.734 --> 00:12:37.801
that people had,
and different features

00:12:37.801 --> 00:12:39.467
that they really expected
the product to have.

00:12:39.467 --> 00:12:40.934
Collins-Sussman: The trends
become really obvious

00:12:40.934 --> 00:12:42.667
if you start
deliberately listening

00:12:42.667 --> 00:12:45.901
and open--creating some kind of
open forum to get feedback.

00:12:45.901 --> 00:12:48.400
It becomes very obvious
what's important and what's not.

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:49.701
rather than, you know,

00:12:49.701 --> 00:12:53.467
just what you happen
to think is important

00:12:53.467 --> 00:12:54.701
it's really
important to listen

00:12:54.701 --> 00:12:55.901
and get that data
from the outside,

00:12:55.901 --> 00:12:57.501
not just from the inside.

00:12:57.501 --> 00:13:00.367
But there's a fear there.

00:13:00.367 --> 00:13:02.167
People tend to be
afraid of doing that.

00:13:02.167 --> 00:13:05.367
First of all, because they get
a lot of crazy ideas, okay?

00:13:05.367 --> 00:13:07.734
And they feel like, oh, God,
if people start saying this

00:13:07.734 --> 00:13:08.734
I'm gonna have to
wind up writing this,

00:13:08.734 --> 00:13:10.234
which is not true.

00:13:10.234 --> 00:13:11.834
Collins-Sussman: You don't
have to listen to every quack.

00:13:11.834 --> 00:13:13.100
Fitzpatrick:
You don't have to listen

00:13:13.100 --> 00:13:15.501
to every single idea
that comes in the long tail.

00:13:15.501 --> 00:13:18.033
Just pay attention
to the ideas

00:13:18.033 --> 00:13:19.667
that you're hearing
over and over again,

00:13:19.667 --> 00:13:21.133
or the questions,
or the themes,

00:13:21.133 --> 00:13:22.467
or the bugs,
that sort of thing.

00:13:22.467 --> 00:13:25.567
Try to do fewer
things better.

00:13:25.567 --> 00:13:28.133
And we sort of use
a metric of target in the 80%.

00:13:28.133 --> 00:13:29.467
As opposed to the 100%.

00:13:29.467 --> 00:13:30.901
Collins-Sussman:
Right, it's really--

00:13:30.901 --> 00:13:34.000
I think it's really great
that if your product can do 80%,

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.234
it can solve 80% of everybody's
pain really really well,

00:13:37.234 --> 00:13:38.534
you're great.

00:13:38.534 --> 00:13:40.434
You see a lot of failure
happens when people

00:13:40.434 --> 00:13:42.667
try to be absolutely
everything to everyone.

00:13:42.667 --> 00:13:44.167
Every bell and whistle
in the world.

00:13:44.167 --> 00:13:46.868
I mean, I guess one example
is Emacs, right? [laughs]

00:13:46.868 --> 00:13:47.868
Fitzpatrick:
Exactly.

00:13:47.868 --> 00:13:50.400
It's everything
to no one.

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:52.601
Well, a quick survey--
who in the room uses Emacs?

00:13:52.601 --> 00:13:54.467
Raise your hand.

00:13:54.467 --> 00:13:56.033
Who uses the I?

00:13:56.033 --> 00:13:57.767
Okay, fight.

00:13:57.767 --> 00:13:59.334
No, just kidding.
[laughter]

00:13:59.334 --> 00:14:00.534
But seriously,
though, I mean,

00:14:00.534 --> 00:14:02.167
I've been an Emacs user
for 12 years,

00:14:02.167 --> 00:14:05.601
and it makes me crazy 'cause
it's just like the Swiss Army--

00:14:05.601 --> 00:14:07.334
Collins-Sussman: Occasionally
you will see products out there

00:14:07.334 --> 00:14:09.501
that try to be
everything to everyone.

00:14:09.501 --> 00:14:11.567
There's some wacky--
We're not sure what this is.

00:14:11.567 --> 00:14:12.734
I think it's...

00:14:12.734 --> 00:14:14.400
Fitzpatrick: We actually
do know what this is,

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:15.734
so don't email us
afterwards.

00:14:15.734 --> 00:14:17.501
People emailing us explaining
exactly what it is.

00:14:17.501 --> 00:14:19.033
But, you know--

00:14:19.033 --> 00:14:20.334
Collins-Sussman: Well, there's
more than one version of it,

00:14:20.334 --> 00:14:21.601
so it must be
important, right?

00:14:21.601 --> 00:14:23.133
Fitzpatrick: It has a lantern
on the back, too.

00:14:23.133 --> 00:14:24.501
A big, like, tube lamp.

00:14:24.501 --> 00:14:26.133
Collins-Sussman: But it's got
a competitor, right?

00:14:26.133 --> 00:14:28.968
Fitzpatrick: Right, and there's
more of these things.

00:14:28.968 --> 00:14:30.801
Collins-Sussman:
Don't be this. [laughing]

00:14:30.801 --> 00:14:32.501
Fitzpatrick: So this
is an example of something

00:14:32.501 --> 00:14:33.634
that's just utterly
terribly designed

00:14:33.634 --> 00:14:34.868
'cause it's trying to be--

00:14:34.868 --> 00:14:36.267
I think it's trying
to be too many things.

00:14:36.267 --> 00:14:37.734
I understand it's an emergency
gadget, remember that.

00:14:37.734 --> 00:14:39.300
Collins-Sussman: Okay.
But what's a good example?

00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:41.634
Fitzpatrick:
Here's a great example, okay?

00:14:41.634 --> 00:14:43.434
You can't boil
an egg in this,

00:14:43.434 --> 00:14:46.801
you can't--you know, you can't
cook a whole turkey in it.

00:14:46.801 --> 00:14:47.968
It's a toaster oven.

00:14:47.968 --> 00:14:49.767
You can make toast,
you can toast a bagel,

00:14:49.767 --> 00:14:51.300
you can do some small
pieces of fish, maybe...

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:52.300
Collins-Sussman:
Make pizza.

00:14:52.300 --> 00:14:53.968
Fitzpatrick:
It does it really well.

00:14:53.968 --> 00:14:55.234
And after we gave
this talk last year,

00:14:55.234 --> 00:14:56.234
someone sent me
a picture of a toaster

00:14:56.234 --> 00:14:57.234
with a radio
on the side of it.

00:14:57.234 --> 00:14:58.567
Collins-Sussman:
Argh...

00:14:58.567 --> 00:14:59.567
Fitzpatrick: I'm like,
you don't get the point;

00:14:59.567 --> 00:15:00.968
that's not the point.

00:15:00.968 --> 00:15:03.033
Collins-Sussman: So this is--
this does a lot of things.

00:15:03.033 --> 00:15:04.434
Most things
for most people.

00:15:04.434 --> 00:15:06.200
Incredibly useful
to a wide variety of people.

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:07.567
Doesn't do
absolutely everything,

00:15:07.567 --> 00:15:09.634
but boy, you know,
it hits that sweet spot.

00:15:09.634 --> 00:15:11.667
So the next thing
you need to think about,

00:15:11.667 --> 00:15:13.901
I guess, is trust.

00:15:13.901 --> 00:15:16.400
And what we mean
by that is it is--

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:17.901
Nice effect.

00:15:17.901 --> 00:15:20.267
It's an irreplaceable
resource.

00:15:20.267 --> 00:15:21.968
Trust is one of these
things that you--

00:15:21.968 --> 00:15:23.701
It's a reputation
that you build up

00:15:23.701 --> 00:15:26.334
with your users, and it's
one of those things that--

00:15:26.334 --> 00:15:28.200
Makes me think of it
as, like, a bank account.

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:30.901
Every time you do something
well, or you listen to people,

00:15:30.901 --> 00:15:34.100
or, you know, you help solve
their problem in some way,

00:15:34.100 --> 00:15:35.267
you get a little
bit of money,

00:15:35.267 --> 00:15:36.934
you put it
in that bank account of trust.

00:15:36.934 --> 00:15:39.801
But it's very, very easy
to destroy that bank account.

00:15:39.801 --> 00:15:41.801
You do one evil thing,

00:15:41.801 --> 00:15:44.434
or one thing that's
a slap in the face of the users,

00:15:44.434 --> 00:15:45.534
and all the trust is gone.

00:15:45.534 --> 00:15:47.000
Fitzpatrick:
Well, people typically

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:48.834
do that
for short-term gains.

00:15:48.834 --> 00:15:51.367
Your temptation to betray
user's trust, I think,

00:15:51.367 --> 00:15:54.467
is for short-term gain, which
results in a long-term loss.

00:15:54.467 --> 00:15:56.100
If you get users
to trust you,

00:15:56.100 --> 00:15:57.400
and they like your product,

00:15:57.400 --> 00:15:59.100
they'll stay with you
through thick and thin

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:00.534
for a very long time.

00:16:00.534 --> 00:16:02.267
And the best
example of this

00:16:02.267 --> 00:16:05.400
is how many people
in this room own a car?

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:07.934
How many people in this room
have a mechanic that they trust?

00:16:07.934 --> 00:16:09.267
Collins-Sussman:
[laughs]

00:16:09.267 --> 00:16:11.567
Fitzpatrick: Okay, see me
after this talk, please.

00:16:11.567 --> 00:16:13.634
No, but seriously,
this is a great example of--

00:16:13.634 --> 00:16:14.868
Collins-Sussman:
Why is that?

00:16:14.868 --> 00:16:17.033
Fitzpatrick: I think mechanics,
for the most part,

00:16:17.033 --> 00:16:19.167
aren't interested
in long-term customers.

00:16:19.167 --> 00:16:20.334
I think it's harder
to do that.

00:16:20.334 --> 00:16:21.434
Collins-Sussman:
It's an assembly line.

00:16:21.434 --> 00:16:23.200
Right?
In these typical situations--

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:24.367
Oh, my car
needs maintenance.

00:16:24.367 --> 00:16:26.400
I'll go take it
to some random dealer,

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:28.467
who I have no real personal
relationship with,

00:16:28.467 --> 00:16:30.167
and they put it
through an assembly line.

00:16:30.167 --> 00:16:31.467
Then they always
try to up-sell you

00:16:31.467 --> 00:16:33.200
to do something that you
don't really need, right?

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:35.601
And we kind of
expect it at this point.

00:16:35.601 --> 00:16:38.434
Fitzpatrick: My grandfather
owned--managed a Firestone store

00:16:38.434 --> 00:16:41.868
for 35 years,
and after the first 20 years,

00:16:41.868 --> 00:16:44.067
95% of his customers
were returning.

00:16:44.067 --> 00:16:45.567
Return customers.

00:16:45.567 --> 00:16:47.100
And that's because
he never tried to sell 'em--

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:48.467
They come in
for a flat tire,

00:16:48.467 --> 00:16:50.067
he'd never try and sell 'em
a radiator flush.

00:16:50.067 --> 00:16:51.400
"Oh, it looks like
you need

00:16:51.400 --> 00:16:54.100
your flob-dangle zip-zopped
or something like that."

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:55.434
Collins-Sussman: Absolutely.
Fitzpatrick: People--

00:16:55.434 --> 00:16:57.501
I don't think people--

00:16:57.501 --> 00:16:58.801
Whether you know a lot
about a car or not,

00:16:58.801 --> 00:16:59.934
I think it leaves you

00:16:59.934 --> 00:17:01.400
with a sort of sick feeling
in your throat,

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:05.334
like, "I'm being played,"
you know, to some extent.

00:17:05.334 --> 00:17:07.200
But we've got an example of that
in Subversion as well, right?

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:08.834
Collins-Sussman: We worked
on the Subversion Project

00:17:08.834 --> 00:17:10.133
for many years,
and one of the things

00:17:10.133 --> 00:17:12.300
we set out
at the beginning

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:15.067
is Subversion is basically
gonna be a set of APIs

00:17:15.067 --> 00:17:16.601
with a small binary
that uses them.

00:17:16.601 --> 00:17:18.467
'Cause we wanted people
to connect to them

00:17:18.467 --> 00:17:20.300
and write alternate clients
and things.

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:22.968
But our APIs are very,
very structured.

00:17:22.968 --> 00:17:24.133
They occur at many levels,

00:17:24.133 --> 00:17:25.767
and they're full
of all sorts of promises

00:17:25.767 --> 00:17:28.334
that "we will not change this,
we will not change this."

00:17:28.334 --> 00:17:30.100
When new versions
of the product come out,

00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:31.834
we very explicitly
mark it.

00:17:31.834 --> 00:17:33.300
Old APIs as deprecated,

00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:35.434
we do not get rid of them,
we make sure they work,

00:17:35.434 --> 00:17:37.267
we keep them testing,
and that's just about--

00:17:37.267 --> 00:17:38.367
you know, that's a certain

00:17:38.367 --> 00:17:40.000
kind of relationship
with programmers.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.100
They are another
kind of user--

00:17:42.100 --> 00:17:43.234
Fitzpatrick:
But we reap the benefit--

00:17:43.234 --> 00:17:44.767
We still get the benefits
of that today

00:17:44.767 --> 00:17:46.167
'cause Tortoise SVN was--

00:17:46.167 --> 00:17:48.167
which is an amazing piece
of software.

00:17:48.167 --> 00:17:49.734
You know, those guys wrote

00:17:49.734 --> 00:17:52.133
a really complex piece
of software

00:17:52.133 --> 00:17:55.267
where that just made Subversion
much more popular in general.

00:17:55.267 --> 00:17:56.501
Collins-Sussman:
Absolutely.

00:17:56.501 --> 00:17:58.501
The thing you need
to think about

00:17:58.501 --> 00:18:00.567
when you're listening
to a user, right.

00:18:00.567 --> 00:18:02.334
Someone's giving you
a piece of feedback--

00:18:02.334 --> 00:18:04.267
You often have to read
between the lines.

00:18:04.267 --> 00:18:05.734
What we mean by that is

00:18:05.734 --> 00:18:07.367
do what I want,
not what I say.

00:18:07.367 --> 00:18:10.100
So, I mean, I had this problem--
like, for example,

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:13.033
trying to teach your parents,
who may not be tech savvy,

00:18:13.033 --> 00:18:14.367
how to use a computer.

00:18:14.367 --> 00:18:16.534
Maybe you're on the phone
with them or something.

00:18:16.534 --> 00:18:18.567
They're saying one thing,

00:18:18.567 --> 00:18:20.033
and usually you have
to sort of listen,

00:18:20.033 --> 00:18:21.767
and it becomes a skill,

00:18:21.767 --> 00:18:23.534
like, well, I think
what they really mean is X,

00:18:23.534 --> 00:18:24.901
or they're
describing something

00:18:24.901 --> 00:18:26.300
in a way that's
not familiar to you.

00:18:26.300 --> 00:18:27.868
Doesn't mean they're dumb,

00:18:27.868 --> 00:18:29.467
it just means they don't know
the same lingo as you, right?

00:18:29.467 --> 00:18:31.234
Or maybe they don't know
how computers work--

00:18:31.234 --> 00:18:33.000
Fitzpatrick: People have
a different mental model.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:34.701
I mean, people have
a very different mental model

00:18:34.701 --> 00:18:36.501
of computers--
how computers work.

00:18:36.501 --> 00:18:38.167
Especially if they're
not engineers.

00:18:38.167 --> 00:18:40.267
And I'm gonna digress
for a moment and tell a story

00:18:40.267 --> 00:18:42.400
about a pencil sharpener

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:44.501
to give you an idea
of how different

00:18:44.501 --> 00:18:46.434
peoples' mental models are.

00:18:46.434 --> 00:18:48.601
A couple years ago,
my grandmother said, you know,

00:18:48.601 --> 00:18:51.200
"Is your grandfather's computer
still any good?"

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:54.167
Now it's
a 1990 Macintosh SE.

00:18:54.167 --> 00:18:56.501
You know, and it hasn't been
used in six or seven years.

00:18:56.501 --> 00:18:58.167
I said, "Oh, you know,
I really don't think so.

00:18:58.167 --> 00:18:59.267
"It's black and white,

00:18:59.267 --> 00:19:00.801
"it doesn't have
an Internet connection,

00:19:00.801 --> 00:19:03.467
"you know, it's probably
best to just, you know,

00:19:03.467 --> 00:19:05.567
give it away
or recycle it or something."

00:19:05.567 --> 00:19:06.834
She said, "Oh, okay,

00:19:06.834 --> 00:19:08.033
'cause I only ever
turn it on anymore

00:19:08.033 --> 00:19:10.200
when I need
to sharpen a pencil.

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:11.701
Collins-Sussman:
[laughs]

00:19:11.701 --> 00:19:13.400
Fitzpatrick: And I stopped,
and I scratched my head,

00:19:13.400 --> 00:19:15.467
and I lis--played that back
again in my head,

00:19:15.467 --> 00:19:17.100
and I realized
I really have to know.

00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:18.400
I probably don't
want to know,

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:20.234
but I have to know
what she's talking about.

00:19:20.234 --> 00:19:21.701
So I start asking
some questions.

00:19:21.701 --> 00:19:23.701
"Well, that's
interesting, grandma."

00:19:23.701 --> 00:19:27.367
And it turns out that she has
an electric pencil sharpener

00:19:27.367 --> 00:19:29.200
that's plugged
into a power strip,

00:19:29.200 --> 00:19:32.400
into which this Macintosh
has been plugged into.

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:35.167
So once a week
she'd take her pencils,

00:19:35.167 --> 00:19:37.868
she would go
into the office,

00:19:37.868 --> 00:19:39.167
she would turn on
the power strip,

00:19:39.167 --> 00:19:40.734
and the little Mac
would go, "beep,"

00:19:40.734 --> 00:19:42.467
and it would start
firing up his hard drive

00:19:42.467 --> 00:19:43.868
and reading
its operating system,

00:19:43.868 --> 00:19:47.100
and she'd sharpen her pencils,
and she'd kill it.

00:19:47.100 --> 00:19:49.033
Collins-Sussman: Cut the power.
Fitzpatrick: Mercilessly.

00:19:49.033 --> 00:19:51.400
Before it even
booted up.

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:53.067
I-I--To let you know...
Collins-Sussman: Poor Mac.

00:19:53.067 --> 00:19:56.067
Fitzpatrick: I rescued
this poor Mac from its fate,

00:19:56.067 --> 00:19:57.501
and it's been
put out to pasture

00:19:57.501 --> 00:20:00.868
with all the other Macs
and Commodore 64s and whatnot.

00:20:00.868 --> 00:20:02.634
Collins-Sussman: That is a good
story about mental models.

00:20:02.634 --> 00:20:03.968
Fitzpatrick:
Right.

00:20:03.968 --> 00:20:05.567
I mean, this made
perfect sense to her, right?

00:20:05.567 --> 00:20:09.467
But beyond that,
seriously--

00:20:09.467 --> 00:20:11.000
Beyond just listening
to your users

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:12.934
and focusing on giving them
good service,

00:20:12.934 --> 00:20:14.467
take the opportunity
to delight them, you know?

00:20:14.467 --> 00:20:15.801
Collins-Sussman:
This is an art.

00:20:15.801 --> 00:20:17.367
Fitzpatrick: Being whimsical
isn't actually bad.

00:20:17.367 --> 00:20:18.634
I think it is an art.

00:20:18.634 --> 00:20:20.300
And it's somewhat
of a cultural thing

00:20:20.300 --> 00:20:21.734
across some pieces
of software.

00:20:21.734 --> 00:20:24.200
Some pieces of software,
I think, do this really well.

00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:25.400
Collins-Sussman: Well,
they'll put Easter eggs in,

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:26.467
or they'll do silly things,

00:20:26.467 --> 00:20:27.767
but just something
so they're

00:20:27.767 --> 00:20:29.934
not taking the host
quite so seriously.

00:20:29.934 --> 00:20:32.501
They understand that there's
some empathy going on

00:20:32.501 --> 00:20:35.100
between the software
and the company, and the user.

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:36.701
It's not just
this formal relationship.

00:20:36.701 --> 00:20:38.200
Fitzpatrick:
Right, right.

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:39.868
Collins-Sussman: So I mean
Google's an example of that.

00:20:39.868 --> 00:20:41.200
We do a lot
of silly things.

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:43.334
We've got doodles that,
you know, happen year-round,

00:20:43.334 --> 00:20:45.400
and we get unbelievable
amounts of email

00:20:45.400 --> 00:20:46.901
about particular doodles--

00:20:46.901 --> 00:20:48.968
why we did do a certain doodle,
or didn't do a certain doodle.

00:20:48.968 --> 00:20:50.501
Fitzpatrick: But no matter
what they do,

00:20:50.501 --> 00:20:51.901
they get a big pile
of, "We love this!"

00:20:51.901 --> 00:20:53.501
and a big pile
of, "We hate this!"

00:20:53.501 --> 00:20:54.901
Collins-Sussman: I'll talk
to my relatives; they're like,

00:20:54.901 --> 00:20:57.234
"Oh, did you see the doodle
that Google did last week?"

00:20:57.234 --> 00:20:59.133
and I'm like,
"Uh, I guess so."

00:20:59.133 --> 00:21:02.033
Fitzpatrick: We're talking about
inspiring passion in users.

00:21:02.033 --> 00:21:05.701
I personally don't care
if you guys love this talk,

00:21:05.701 --> 00:21:07.901
or hate everything we say
and disagree with it all,

00:21:07.901 --> 00:21:10.300
as long as we spark
some reaction in folks

00:21:10.300 --> 00:21:12.067
and make you think
a little bit about something.

00:21:12.067 --> 00:21:14.000
You know,
if you're asleep,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.501
then that probably means
we failed somewhere.

00:21:16.501 --> 00:21:17.701
Collins-Sussman:
Google has a long history

00:21:17.701 --> 00:21:19.968
of doing April Fool's jokes
as well.

00:21:19.968 --> 00:21:21.534
Which--Every year
it's something different.

00:21:21.534 --> 00:21:26.200
In 2008, every single link
on the YouTube front page

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:27.467
went to a Rick Roll.

00:21:27.467 --> 00:21:29.434
Okay, great. It's funny.
Right? One day.

00:21:29.434 --> 00:21:30.767
Fitzpatrick: But why
would you do that?

00:21:30.767 --> 00:21:33.267
You know, most people
don't even, like--

00:21:33.267 --> 00:21:35.601
It seems so impractical
and so whimsical.

00:21:35.601 --> 00:21:37.167
But people
remember that,

00:21:37.167 --> 00:21:39.267
and they're like, "Oh, God,
I remember; I was there."

00:21:39.267 --> 00:21:41.434
Collins-Sussman: I think another
great case is you can use humor

00:21:41.434 --> 00:21:43.934
to sort of encourage people
to do the right thing.

00:21:43.934 --> 00:21:45.267
There was
a social networking site

00:21:45.267 --> 00:21:47.567
that went up for a little while
where they really wanted

00:21:47.567 --> 00:21:49.434
people to upload photos,
and a lot of people

00:21:49.434 --> 00:21:50.634
won't do that
at first when they join

00:21:50.634 --> 00:21:51.801
a social networking site.

00:21:51.801 --> 00:21:53.267
So this site,
what they decided to do

00:21:53.267 --> 00:21:56.701
was put in a default image of
Dick Cheney to every new user.

00:21:56.701 --> 00:21:59.934
And, oh, my goodness, everybody
uploaded a new photo right away.

00:21:59.934 --> 00:22:03.634
Fitzpatrick: Over 90% of their
users uploaded a new photo.

00:22:03.634 --> 00:22:06.467
Collins-Sussman: Clearly
something humorous there, right?

00:22:06.467 --> 00:22:10.400
But that's just another way
of delighting the users.

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:13.901
So the third thing we want to
talk about is focusing on users.

00:22:13.901 --> 00:22:15.767
We talked about marketing
and customer service.

00:22:15.767 --> 00:22:17.634
What does it mean
to actually focus on them

00:22:17.634 --> 00:22:19.000
and have them affect
your everyday activities?

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:20.100
Fitzpatrick:
What do you think about

00:22:20.100 --> 00:22:21.567
when you hear
"focusing on users"?

00:22:21.567 --> 00:22:23.434
You usually think about
the orbiting brain lasers.

00:22:23.434 --> 00:22:24.901
Collins-Sussman:
No, no, not released. Next.

00:22:24.901 --> 00:22:27.467
Fitzpatrick: Oh, we don't
talk about prerelease. Sorry.

00:22:27.467 --> 00:22:28.667
Collins-Sussman:
[laughs]

00:22:28.667 --> 00:22:29.834
Usability.

00:22:29.834 --> 00:22:31.000
Fitzpatrick: It sort of
falls under usability.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:32.801
It falls under making
your software something

00:22:32.801 --> 00:22:36.501
that people can comprehend
and do great things with.

00:22:36.501 --> 00:22:38.801
If you just can't
try out your software,

00:22:38.801 --> 00:22:40.734
you don't have
any users, right?

00:22:40.734 --> 00:22:42.501
And like we said earlier,

00:22:42.501 --> 00:22:44.834
the first impressions are really
key to this sort of thing.

00:22:44.834 --> 00:22:46.400
Collins-Sussman:
And the barrier to entry.

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:48.067
Fitzpatrick:
The metaphor we like to use

00:22:48.067 --> 00:22:49.200
is one of a storefront.

00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:50.501
Okay, if you're walking
down the street,

00:22:50.501 --> 00:22:52.067
you look in a store window,
and you see something--

00:22:52.067 --> 00:22:53.801
"Oh, hey, there's
a doodad I want to buy."

00:22:53.801 --> 00:22:55.400
You walk inside
and you inspect it.

00:22:55.400 --> 00:22:57.267
Okay, that costs you
nothing but a few steps.

00:22:57.267 --> 00:22:58.567
If you walk up to the door
and they say,

00:22:58.567 --> 00:23:01.567
"Stop. We'd like you
to fill out this form.

00:23:01.567 --> 00:23:04.534
All this information
about yourself."

00:23:04.534 --> 00:23:06.400
You're gonna be like,
"Really? I just wanted to--

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:07.834
It's not that
important to me."

00:23:07.834 --> 00:23:09.133
And they're gonna go away
before they even had a chance...

00:23:09.133 --> 00:23:10.467
Collins-Sussman:
Read this documentation, right?

00:23:10.467 --> 00:23:11.834
Read this
license agreement.

00:23:11.834 --> 00:23:13.167
Fitzpatrick: Exactly.
Collins-Sussman: It's crazy.

00:23:13.167 --> 00:23:16.567
Back to the Emacs and vi,
which we mentioned before,

00:23:16.567 --> 00:23:18.868
when I first
was introduced to Unix,

00:23:18.868 --> 00:23:20.133
years and years ago,

00:23:20.133 --> 00:23:22.367
I remember saying,
"Which editor should I learn?

00:23:22.367 --> 00:23:24.300
Emacs or vi?" and everyone in
the room kind of laughed at me

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:25.634
and said,
"Well, you figure it out.

00:23:25.634 --> 00:23:27.167
Which one you want.
We're not gonna tell you."

00:23:27.167 --> 00:23:28.601
So I started up vi,

00:23:28.601 --> 00:23:30.634
and I really didn't know
what to do,

00:23:30.634 --> 00:23:32.400
and I was typing things
and nothing was happening,

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:33.734
and I kind of got frustrated.

00:23:33.734 --> 00:23:35.834
And I started up Emacs,
and I just started typing.

00:23:35.834 --> 00:23:37.000
There were
characters appearing.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.234
"Oh, this is just like
a word processor."

00:23:39.234 --> 00:23:40.567
Fitzpatrick: How did you
figure out how to quit it?

00:23:40.567 --> 00:23:41.767
Collins-Sussman:
Well, that was--I couldn't qu--

00:23:41.767 --> 00:23:42.934
Fitzpatrick: I had
to unplug the computer

00:23:42.934 --> 00:23:44.901
to quit Emacs
the first time I tried.

00:23:44.901 --> 00:23:46.467
I'm like,
"You got to be kidding me."

00:23:46.467 --> 00:23:47.834
Collins-Sussman:
I couldn't quit vi either,

00:23:47.834 --> 00:23:49.467
but the point is,
at least, you know,

00:23:49.467 --> 00:23:51.000
in the first ten seconds

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:52.567
I just had an initial
impression of, like,

00:23:52.567 --> 00:23:54.100
"Oh, look, here's something
that's familiar to me.

00:23:54.100 --> 00:23:57.067
At least it's behaving
somewhat like what I expect."

00:23:57.067 --> 00:23:59.000
Now, maybe that's not
the perfect example,

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.901
but I think it's a nice anecdote
about first impressions.

00:24:01.901 --> 00:24:03.200
Fitzpatrick:
Well, there's a lot of examples.

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:04.734
I mean, Perl and PHP
I don't--

00:24:04.734 --> 00:24:06.734
They're not generally considered
really powerful things

00:24:06.734 --> 00:24:10.000
for writing Web apps or general
apps, but they're really easy.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:13.167
There's a really low barrier
to entry with these things.

00:24:13.167 --> 00:24:14.634
Or Fink, for example.

00:24:14.634 --> 00:24:17.200
If anybody uses Mac OS X,
there's this thing called Fink

00:24:17.200 --> 00:24:19.367
that has all this
extra packages and stuff.

00:24:19.367 --> 00:24:22.133
In Tiger, they had this
really nice disk image.

00:24:22.133 --> 00:24:24.667
You just double-click it,
you install it, and it's done.

00:24:24.667 --> 00:24:27.133
As soon as Leopard came out,
they didn't have this ready,

00:24:27.133 --> 00:24:29.167
and so you had to download
things and build things

00:24:29.167 --> 00:24:30.334
and go through
all this crazy stuff.

00:24:30.334 --> 00:24:31.467
Collins-Sussman:
Everybody stopped using it.

00:24:31.467 --> 00:24:32.567
Fitzpatrick:
Well, people eventually started.

00:24:32.567 --> 00:24:33.667
Collins-Sussman:
Well, a lot of people did.

00:24:33.667 --> 00:24:35.033
Fitzpatrick: But it was
a higher barrier,

00:24:35.033 --> 00:24:36.267
and you're more
likely to say,

00:24:36.267 --> 00:24:38.133
"Oh, heck with it,
I can live without this stuff."

00:24:38.133 --> 00:24:40.200
Collins-Sussman: So one way
we like to think about usability

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:42.334
is we have this bell curve.

00:24:42.334 --> 00:24:43.968
On one end we have
Donald Knuth,

00:24:43.968 --> 00:24:45.868
on the other hand
we have Fitz's grandmother.

00:24:45.868 --> 00:24:46.901
Fitzpatrick:
Who I love dearly, really.

00:24:46.901 --> 00:24:48.200
Collins-Sussman:
We do love her.

00:24:48.200 --> 00:24:49.901
I've never met her.

00:24:49.901 --> 00:24:52.901
So the question is
where does your software fall

00:24:52.901 --> 00:24:55.133
in terms of--we just want
to think about drawing a line.

00:24:55.133 --> 00:24:57.601
Every user
to the right of the line

00:24:57.601 --> 00:25:00.734
is able to use your software
with not much effort.

00:25:00.734 --> 00:25:04.033
So we can sort of talk about
various pieces of software.

00:25:04.033 --> 00:25:05.734
Fitzpatrick:
We're version control geeks,

00:25:05.734 --> 00:25:09.033
so we think Subversion
actually falls pretty easy.

00:25:09.033 --> 00:25:10.901
In the easy to use.

00:25:10.901 --> 00:25:12.200
So there's a lot of people

00:25:12.200 --> 00:25:13.667
that it's accessible to,
quite frankly.

00:25:13.667 --> 00:25:15.100
Collins-Sussman:
Even people who've never

00:25:15.100 --> 00:25:16.267
used version control before

00:25:16.267 --> 00:25:18.300
find it not too hard
to get used to.

00:25:18.300 --> 00:25:22.067
Fitzpatrick: Right,
and another example is Git.

00:25:22.067 --> 00:25:23.901
Collins-Sussman:
[laughs]

00:25:23.901 --> 00:25:25.701
Fitzpatrick: It's technically
a great piece of software,

00:25:25.701 --> 00:25:27.100
but it's quite
hard to use.

00:25:27.100 --> 00:25:28.534
Collins-Sussman: And you can
