00:36:38.200 --> 00:36:40.267
I've had other people
tell me this as well.

00:36:40.267 --> 00:36:41.767
Is that, all right,
Google's corporation's got

00:36:41.767 --> 00:36:42.934
a lot of people,
but a lot of people

00:36:42.934 --> 00:36:44.334
don't actually
realize that.

00:36:44.334 --> 00:36:47.634
There's a lot of people
out there who really--

00:36:47.634 --> 00:36:49.934
they just think Google's
part of their computer,

00:36:49.934 --> 00:36:51.901
or they think it's part
of their Web browser,

00:36:51.901 --> 00:36:53.934
and I've actually
met people who I'll say,

00:36:53.934 --> 00:36:55.501
"Oh, I work for Google,"

00:36:55.501 --> 00:36:58.167
and they're like, "Oh, I didn't
know anybody worked there."

00:36:58.167 --> 00:36:59.200
Fitzpatrick:
Exactly, yeah.

00:36:59.200 --> 00:37:00.467
My mother-in-law
introduced me

00:37:00.467 --> 00:37:01.968
to some 82-year-old
friend of hers, and she said,

00:37:01.968 --> 00:37:03.701
"This is my son-in-law,
he works for Google,"

00:37:03.701 --> 00:37:06.033
and she looks at her and looks
at me like what am I doing here?

00:37:06.033 --> 00:37:08.234
She said, "I didn't know anybody
worked at the Google."

00:37:08.234 --> 00:37:09.567
Collins-Sussman: Well, we've had
the opposite, right?

00:37:09.567 --> 00:37:10.934
Fitzpatrick:
Right, well--

00:37:10.934 --> 00:37:12.167
Collins-Sussman: This is
my favorite so you tell this.

00:37:12.167 --> 00:37:14.167
Fitzpatrick: One of
our other friends out here

00:37:14.167 --> 00:37:16.501
told his aunt
that, you know,

00:37:16.501 --> 00:37:18.133
everyone was going to Disneyland
a couple years ago.

00:37:18.133 --> 00:37:19.300
Collins-Sussman:
All the Google employees.

00:37:19.300 --> 00:37:20.567
Fitzpatrick:
All the Google employees were

00:37:20.567 --> 00:37:22.601
taking a couple days and we were
gonna go to Disneyland.

00:37:22.601 --> 00:37:24.834
And his aunt said,
"Well, you can't do that."

00:37:24.834 --> 00:37:27.000
He's like, "What do you mean
I can't do that?"

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.133
She's like, "Well, who's gonna
do my searches for me?"

00:37:29.133 --> 00:37:30.567
Collins-Sussman:
[laughs]

00:37:30.567 --> 00:37:32.334
I sort of imagine, like,
you know, switchboard operators.

00:37:32.334 --> 00:37:33.701
Fitzpatrick: Right.

00:37:33.701 --> 00:37:35.467
Somebody with the Yellow Pages
looking things up.

00:37:35.467 --> 00:37:38.067
But I mean, again this is
the way people perceive things,

00:37:38.067 --> 00:37:40.400
and the point of that
is just to think about the fact

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:43.467
that the way that
you perceive your software

00:37:43.467 --> 00:37:45.801
from the inside looking out
is very different

00:37:45.801 --> 00:37:48.901
than people who aren't as
technical, who aren't engineers,

00:37:48.901 --> 00:37:50.334
perceive your software.

00:37:50.334 --> 00:37:51.334
Collins-Sussman:
So it's really--

00:37:51.334 --> 00:37:53.701
it's not just
about the code.

00:37:53.701 --> 00:37:55.434
I mean, yes, we all have an
inherent distrust of marketing,

00:37:55.434 --> 00:37:57.434
and spin,
and interacting with users.

00:37:57.434 --> 00:38:00.267
It's something that sort of
scares us as programmers.

00:38:00.267 --> 00:38:01.767
But there's actually--
there is--

00:38:01.767 --> 00:38:04.701
You are able to have
a healthy relationship

00:38:04.701 --> 00:38:07.601
with these facts,
with these people on your team,

00:38:07.601 --> 00:38:09.734
you just need to find
that nice balance

00:38:09.734 --> 00:38:13.334
where you are promising
the right amount of thing,

00:38:13.334 --> 00:38:15.000
they are promising
the right amount of thing,

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:18.234
they're adding the appropriate
amount of sizzle to your steak,

00:38:18.234 --> 00:38:20.033
and you end up with something
that's really, really usable.

00:38:20.033 --> 00:38:22.601
Fitzpatrick: And you're
listening to your users as well.

00:38:22.601 --> 00:38:24.033
And that's all we have
to say about that.

