00:41:38.534 --> 00:41:40.601
Yes.

00:41:40.601 --> 00:41:42.434
audience member: Yes, I wonder
how both of you think

00:41:42.434 --> 00:41:46.033
about designing software for
the way users currently think

00:41:46.033 --> 00:41:49.234
versus taking them into
a new model of doing things.

00:41:49.234 --> 00:41:51.901
And one example
that jumps to mind was Gmail.

00:41:51.901 --> 00:41:53.767
How there was
no Delete button at first,

00:41:53.767 --> 00:41:55.934
and we're trying to push them
towards a totally new model

00:41:55.934 --> 00:42:00.033
and then eventually caving
and adding the Delete button.

00:42:00.033 --> 00:42:03.167
Fitzpatrick: I personally agree
with the Delete button.

00:42:03.167 --> 00:42:05.434
Even though I rarely use it,
it's nice to know--

00:42:05.434 --> 00:42:06.767
It's like
an emergency exit, you know.

00:42:06.767 --> 00:42:07.934
I don't want
to have to use it,

00:42:07.934 --> 00:42:09.467
but it's nice
to know it's there.

00:42:09.467 --> 00:42:10.901
Collins-Sussman: I think there's
a tightrope you need to walk.

00:42:10.901 --> 00:42:13.234
I mean, if you have
a new, radical way

00:42:13.234 --> 00:42:15.300
of working with software,

00:42:15.300 --> 00:42:16.734
I don't think it will
get a lot of uptake

00:42:16.734 --> 00:42:18.868
if it's completely alien.

00:42:18.868 --> 00:42:20.567
I think you need
to find some balance

00:42:20.567 --> 00:42:23.334
between somewhat familiar,
and then users are willing

00:42:23.334 --> 00:42:25.000
to tolerate a little bit
of the unfamiliar

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:28.467
if they see an obvious gain
in productivity or something.

00:42:28.467 --> 00:42:30.868
And I think Gmail
is an example of that.

00:42:30.868 --> 00:42:32.267
It's like, okay,
it's a familiar.

00:42:32.267 --> 00:42:34.000
I've used email before.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.100
But a lot of friends of mine
who started using Gmail

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:38.601
weren't used to seeing
conversations grouped together,

00:42:38.601 --> 00:42:40.334
and that was
a little bit of a shock,

00:42:40.334 --> 00:42:43.801
but it was not so much
that they ran away screaming.

00:42:43.801 --> 00:42:45.334
And now, you know,
months later,

00:42:45.334 --> 00:42:46.834
I can't remember
living without it.

00:42:46.834 --> 00:42:49.033
Fitzpatrick: Right.
But there's huge advantages.

00:42:49.033 --> 00:42:51.601
I mean, you still have to offer
a net gain to your users

00:42:51.601 --> 00:42:53.133
if you're gonna have
something new like that.

