Everybody in engineering
points to the fact

00:43:24.501 --> 00:43:27.033
that Google
tests things a lot.

00:43:27.033 --> 00:43:28.801
Everybody in design points to
the fact

00:43:28.801 --> 00:43:34.033
that one of the famous
Google UI designers quit,

00:43:34.033 --> 00:43:36.534
and her famous thing was,
"It took months to do anything

00:43:36.534 --> 00:43:39.000
'cause we had to test
8,000 shades of gray."

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:42.934
So the question is, you know,
from your experiences,

00:43:42.934 --> 00:43:44.801
where do you
draw the line?

00:43:44.801 --> 00:43:48.467
You know, where do you really
find kind of the best compromise

00:43:48.467 --> 00:43:51.901
between testing
a bajillion shades of gray

00:43:51.901 --> 00:43:54.434
and then just actually
implementing one

00:43:54.434 --> 00:43:56.267
that you know will work?

00:43:56.267 --> 00:43:57.834
Without, like--

00:43:57.834 --> 00:44:00.300
so when you're going forward
and you're building features,

00:44:00.300 --> 00:44:01.801
There's, you know,
the continuum

00:44:01.801 --> 00:44:04.734
of testing every version
of every possible thing,

00:44:04.734 --> 00:44:06.801
or there's just doing it
the way you envision it

00:44:06.801 --> 00:44:09.367
and the way
that you think will work.

00:44:09.367 --> 00:44:10.734
How do you balance that?

00:44:10.734 --> 00:44:13.067
Do you have
any suggestions there?

00:44:13.067 --> 00:44:14.501
Collins-Sussman:
It's an interesting tension.

00:44:14.501 --> 00:44:16.734
Fitzpatrick: Yeah, I think it is
an interesting tension,

00:44:16.734 --> 00:44:19.434
and I probably have
a little different view

00:44:19.434 --> 00:44:20.801
than a lot of people
on that.

00:44:20.801 --> 00:44:23.634
So anybody here familiar
with EveryBlock.com

00:44:23.634 --> 00:44:25.667
or ChicagoCrime.org?

00:44:25.667 --> 00:44:26.968
EveryBlock.com
is an amazing site,

00:44:26.968 --> 00:44:29.167
especially if you live
in one of the cities it covers.

00:44:29.167 --> 00:44:31.567
But Adrian Holovaty, who
started it, is a friend of mine,

00:44:31.567 --> 00:44:33.901
and I was talking
to him, like,

00:44:33.901 --> 00:44:37.067
"Why does, like, the Jango
Web site look so beautiful?

00:44:37.067 --> 00:44:39.000
Why does ChicagoCrime
look so beautiful?"

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:40.300
I'm like,
"You're not a designer.

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:41.501
"I know you're
not a designer.

00:44:41.501 --> 00:44:43.033
You're a journalist
and an engineer."

00:44:43.033 --> 00:44:44.467
And he said,

00:44:44.467 --> 00:44:49.701
"It's because I have a UX
designer who I really trust,

00:44:49.701 --> 00:44:53.367
and I can leave him to make
all the decisions for that."

00:44:53.367 --> 00:44:55.767
User experience
and user design, I think,

00:44:55.767 --> 00:44:57.400
Is actually
incredibly sophisticated,

00:44:57.400 --> 00:44:59.434
but it's a thing
that most engineers--

00:44:59.434 --> 00:45:01.801
myself too,
at some point--

00:45:01.801 --> 00:45:03.334
think that they can
just understand.

00:45:03.334 --> 00:45:04.767
Same for PR.

00:45:04.767 --> 00:45:07.501
I think most engineers are like,
"Oh, this is a soft skill,

00:45:07.501 --> 00:45:09.367
I could figure this out,"
when you really can't.

00:45:09.367 --> 00:45:11.634
And you don't have as much
of a respect for, I think,

00:45:11.634 --> 00:45:12.934
other peoples'
abilities in that.

00:45:12.934 --> 00:45:15.234
So I personally believe
that most of the time

00:45:15.234 --> 00:45:17.734
if you can find
someone who you trust,

00:45:17.734 --> 00:45:19.601
and let them sort of
make that decision...

00:45:19.601 --> 00:45:22.400
If there's not a lot of trust
between those two,

00:45:22.400 --> 00:45:24.667
I would say you might
have some issues,

00:45:24.667 --> 00:45:28.267
especially if you don't respect
what they're doing or saying.

00:45:28.267 --> 00:45:29.667
Collins-Sussman: I think that
the tension you're pointing out

00:45:29.667 --> 00:45:32.400
is between art
and science.

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:34.601
There's an art to it,
and there's a science to it.

00:45:34.601 --> 00:45:37.167
Some people have good taste,
some people have terrible taste.

00:45:37.167 --> 00:45:39.767
Fitzpatrick: That's subjective.
We always have good taste.

00:45:39.767 --> 00:45:40.934
Collins-Sussman:
Always. Right.

00:45:40.934 --> 00:45:42.467
Everyone else
always has bad taste.

00:45:42.467 --> 00:45:46.067
But I guess my feeling about it
is you need to find people

00:45:46.067 --> 00:45:49.667
with good taste to get you,
you know, 80% of the way there.

00:45:49.667 --> 00:45:52.767
And maybe they'll make sort of
the artful decisions

00:45:52.767 --> 00:45:56.100
that are more emotional,
less rational,

00:45:56.100 --> 00:45:58.734
to sort of decide maybe
the overall look and feel,

00:45:58.734 --> 00:46:00.901
or what features
are exposed or whatnot,

00:46:00.901 --> 00:46:02.667
and then that last 20%

00:46:02.667 --> 00:46:05.167
can sort of go into the realm
of scientific testing.

00:46:05.167 --> 00:46:06.400
Like, what color
should this be?

00:46:06.400 --> 00:46:08.167
Exactly how wide
should this part be?

00:46:08.167 --> 00:46:11.501
And maybe there really are
measurable usability metrics

00:46:11.501 --> 00:46:13.334
that come from
that scientific bit.

00:46:13.334 --> 00:46:15.601
So there is a tension,
but I think they can cooperate.

00:46:15.601 --> 00:46:16.667
If you--
if you do it right.

00:46:16.667 --> 00:46:18.067
It's not all
one or the other.

00:46:18.067 --> 00:46:19.234
Fitzpatrick:
And I still think

00:46:19.234 --> 00:46:20.868
that there's opportunity
for testing.

00:46:20.868 --> 00:46:22.067
In the engineering side,

00:46:22.067 --> 00:46:23.200
you can make it easy
to do experiments

00:46:23.200 --> 00:46:24.534
or that sort of thing,

00:46:24.534 --> 00:46:25.834
especially if you're
dealing with network apps

00:46:25.834 --> 00:46:26.868
and not something
you have to, you know,

00:46:26.868 --> 00:46:28.534
buy a CD and download it.

00:46:28.534 --> 00:46:32.300
Those days are thankfully
going away, I think.

00:46:32.300 --> 00:46:35.234
But again,
there is a balance there,

00:46:35.234 --> 00:46:36.400
but I think
it really requires

00:46:36.400 --> 00:46:38.734
some sort of trust
and respect

00:46:38.734 --> 00:46:40.667
of the folks
on the other side of the fence.

00:46:40.667 --> 00:46:43.267
Just like it requires trust
and respect for your users.

00:46:43.267 --> 00:46:44.601
That they're staying--

00:46:44.601 --> 00:46:46.834
What they want--What a majority
of them say they want

00:46:46.834 --> 00:46:48.234
is something that's good
to add to your product.

00:46:48.234 --> 00:46:50.534
Collins-Sussman:
UI is a really hard field.

00:46:50.534 --> 00:46:52.200
Fitzpatrick:
It really is.

00:46:52.200 --> 00:46:53.868
And engineers beat the heck
out of UI people.

00:46:53.868 --> 00:46:55.634
Collins-Sussman: Anyone who may
not be a programmer

00:46:55.634 --> 00:46:57.901
must not be
very skilled.

00:46:57.901 --> 00:46:59.634
There's sort of this weird
bias in the industry.

00:46:59.634 --> 00:47:01.100
Fitzpatrick: What are
the different things

00:47:01.100 --> 00:47:02.501
that engineers
think they can do?

00:47:02.501 --> 00:47:06.567
UI design, PR, legal stuff.
All these different things.

00:47:06.567 --> 00:47:08.934
Just read things they had
compiled into a head, right?

00:47:08.934 --> 00:47:10.734
Rarely is it the case.

00:47:10.734 --> 00:47:12.234
Next question.

00:47:12.234 --> 00:47:13.501
audience member:
So as a person that actually

00:47:13.501 --> 00:47:14.968
does a little bit
of everything--

00:47:14.968 --> 00:47:16.334
engineering,
UI design, everything--

00:47:16.334 --> 00:47:18.334
I can say that actually UI
design is pretty difficult.

00:47:18.334 --> 00:47:20.100
Something that
I'm still having

00:47:20.100 --> 00:47:22.400
a hard time getting
a good grasp of it.

00:47:22.400 --> 00:47:26.334
One of the challenges
that we're having is that

00:47:26.334 --> 00:47:30.100
I mean, what's a preferred
method of educating your users?

00:47:30.100 --> 00:47:32.701
So you do have
a piece of technology

00:47:32.701 --> 00:47:35.133
that you can do
fantastic stuff with it,

00:47:35.133 --> 00:47:39.133
but you need to get users
to use it the right way.

00:47:39.133 --> 00:47:40.934
There needs to be
a little bit of education.

00:47:40.934 --> 00:47:42.100
I know it goes
counterintuitive--

00:47:42.100 --> 00:47:43.901
So you have to
make it simple enough

00:47:43.901 --> 00:47:46.200
that everyone can just
get it right off the bat.

00:47:46.200 --> 00:47:47.334
What if there are--

00:47:47.334 --> 00:47:48.801
Like, for some of
the mail application

00:47:48.801 --> 00:47:50.267
you guys showed
from Eudora,

00:47:50.267 --> 00:47:51.968
that was an overkill,

00:47:51.968 --> 00:47:55.067
but what if there
is some essential steps

00:47:55.067 --> 00:47:57.467
that they really
have to take?

00:47:57.467 --> 00:47:59.868
In your experience, what's the
best recommendation to do that?

00:47:59.868 --> 00:48:03.634
Is it videos,
images, step--making--

00:48:03.634 --> 00:48:07.767
splicing it up so people
go into chunks?

00:48:07.767 --> 00:48:09.033
Fitzpatrick:
I'd probably start

00:48:09.033 --> 00:48:10.334
with user testing,
quite frankly.

00:48:10.334 --> 00:48:11.701
'Cause I think once you--

00:48:11.701 --> 00:48:13.467
If you get something and you
put someone in front of it

00:48:13.467 --> 00:48:14.534
who's not a super
tech-savvy person,

00:48:14.534 --> 00:48:16.701
who's unfamiliar
with it,

00:48:16.701 --> 00:48:18.300
and look at what
they do first.

00:48:18.300 --> 00:48:20.467
Look at what confuses them,
look at where they get lost.

00:48:20.467 --> 00:48:23.167
I think that's a very
telling kind of thing.

00:48:23.167 --> 00:48:24.868
Beyond that,
certainly documentation,

00:48:24.868 --> 00:48:26.334
you know, fun videos.

00:48:26.334 --> 00:48:29.834
I mean, remember years ago
Rails did that video

00:48:29.834 --> 00:48:31.567
of how easy it was
to build an app.

00:48:31.567 --> 00:48:33.968
And that was a huge win
for those guys.

00:48:33.968 --> 00:48:35.901
You know, 'cause it was
a couple minutes long,

00:48:35.901 --> 00:48:37.100
and you could see
how easy it was

00:48:37.100 --> 00:48:38.801
to build their
sort of demo app.

00:48:38.801 --> 00:48:41.067
Collins-Sussman: The things that
I've seen actually not work well

00:48:41.067 --> 00:48:44.868
is when a company puts
all their eggs into either--

00:48:44.868 --> 00:48:47.801
People learn sort of
bottom up or top down.

00:48:47.801 --> 00:48:50.567
And some people want the
overview, they want the video,

00:48:50.567 --> 00:48:52.968
they want to read
the manual.

00:48:52.968 --> 00:48:54.901
And some people
just want to jump in

00:48:54.901 --> 00:48:57.133
and play with it
and figure it out as they go.

00:48:57.133 --> 00:48:59.033
And there are
different techniques

00:48:59.033 --> 00:49:01.033
for teaching both ways,

00:49:01.033 --> 00:49:04.367
and one of the things
I see companies don't do

00:49:04.367 --> 00:49:06.367
is they choose
just one technique.

00:49:06.367 --> 00:49:09.601
Like, maybe they'll have
an online help system

00:49:09.601 --> 00:49:11.267
that's just
for bottom-up users,

00:49:11.267 --> 00:49:12.767
but there won't be
an overview anywhere.

00:49:12.767 --> 00:49:15.334
Or maybe they'll do a video
that has a general overview

00:49:15.334 --> 00:49:17.100
of how the system works
and how cool it is,

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:18.868
but then there won't be
any bottom-up learning.

00:49:18.868 --> 00:49:21.167
No, you know, help system

00:49:21.167 --> 00:49:23.300
that's sort of contact sensitive
or anything like that.

00:49:23.300 --> 00:49:26.801
So I think you need to think
about both kinds of users.

00:49:26.801 --> 00:49:28.100
That's my pet peeve.

